SIMPLE: recure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recure
<hw>Re*cure"</hw> <pr>(r?*k?r")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Recover</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To arrive at; to reach; to
attain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Lydgate.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To recover; to regain; to repossess.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When their powers, impaired through labor long,⟦br⟧
With due repast, they had <qex>recured</qex> well.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To restore, as from weariness, sickness; or the
like; to repair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In western waves his weary wagon did <qex>recure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be a cure for; to remedy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No medicine⟦br⟧
Might avail his sickness to <qex>recure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Lydgate.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Recure
<hw>Re*cure"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Cure; remedy; recovery.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But whom he hite, without <qex>recure</qex> he dies.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recureless</ent>⟦br⟧
